Thus we, who can no longer suppose that the universe exists only for us, who must believe that if it is the universe of 3 living God it is full, not only of life, but of specialised forms of life of which we can have no idea—begin dimly to understand also that because our little affairs are of importance to so great a God, they must have far vaster import for Him than we 316 able to conceive.

As regards the modern conception of humanity. To the science of to-day humanity means, and rightly means, an incident in terrestrial evolution. Whether consciousneSS‚ as M. Bergson seems to say, has descended into matter and tunnelled through it, evolving brain and nerve3 or whether brain and nerve and all the powers of mind or spirit have been evolved together; the beginning of the process lies back in the beginning of crea- tion. Are we, then, to suppose that it ends with man's death?
